    <item>
      <title>Creating a public rsa key when you already have a private one</title>
      <link>https://dmrz.dev/2010/12/09/creating-public-rsa-key-when-you-already-have-private-one/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 09 Dec 2010 12:06:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid>https://dmrz.dev/2010/12/09/creating-public-rsa-key-when-you-already-have-private-one/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;To create a public rsa key using a private one, simply type:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#4c4f69;background-color:#eff1f5;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;$ ssh-keygen -y -f /path/to/private_rsa &amp;gt; /path/to/public_rsa
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note that it is not adding user@hostname, so if you need it, add this in the end of public_rsa file with a leading space symbol&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
